Gather and Format

Gather and format from the database

scores <- DBI::dbGetQuery(conn = con, statement = paste0(
  "SELECT DISTINCT sub.* FROM
  (SELECT DISTINCT r.*, c.par, c.course_rating FROM rounds r
  LEFT JOIN courses c
  ON c.tees = r.tees
  AND c.course_name = r.course_name
  AND c.hole = r.hole
  AND c.hole_handicap = r.hole_handicap) AS sub
  INNER JOIN players p
  ON sub.GHIN = p.GHIN
  AND sub.handicap_index = p.handicap_index
  AND sub.date = p.date;"
)) |> 
  dplyr::mutate(date = lubridate::as_date(date),
                hole = stringr::str_extract(hole, pattern = '[0-9]{1,}') |> 
                  as.numeric()) |> 
  dplyr::relocate(par, .after = hole) |> 
  dplyr::relocate(course_rating, .after = tees) |>
  dplyr::group_by(date) |> 
  dplyr::arrange(desc(date), hole) |> 
  dplyr::ungroup()

Fit Models

Fit a lmer model to the data to capture repeated measurements of Gross Score predicted by Handicap Index and course_rating

  • The USGA calculates this index based on an individuals average of the 8 best Gross Scores over their 20 most recently-posted rounds
  • Every course has a rating; the Handicap Index calculation factors in these ratings
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: `Gross Score` ~ `Handicap Index` + course_rating + days + (1 +  
##     `Handicap Index` | course * course_rating)
##    Data: 
## dplyr::relocate(dplyr::mutate(dplyr::ungroup(scores_sum), course_rating = dplyr::case_when(grepl(date_course,  
##     pattern = "Sewailo") ~ 68.9, TRUE ~ course_rating), course_rating = mean(course_rating) -  
##     course_rating, course = gsub(date_course, pattern = "[0-9]|\\-|\\\n|\\.",  
##     replacement = ""), `Handicap Index` = mean(`Handicap Index`),

Interpretation

  • The aggregate average Gross Score (intercept of Fixed effects) is 88.19796 (yikes, thats bad).

  • For every 0.28373 standard deviations away from the average course_rating (how difficult the course is; usually between 68-72 strokes), the Gross Score grows by 1 stroke.

    • This makes sense. Theres a lot of variation in performance (Gross Score) between and within courses, as shown by the Random effects Variance (Intercepts). Otherwise, we would expect course_rating to have a stronger relationship to Gross Score: the coefficient, representing the aggregate effect on Gross Score, i.e.independent of course and Handicap Index, would be larger.

    • A small t-value of this Fixed effect suggests it is a relatively weak predictor of Gross Score. This makes sense when viewing the Scores plot and comparing the relatively flat line of course_rating with the downward trend of Handicap Index and Gross Score.

  • The -0.02425 Fixed effect estimate of days on Gross Score means that as time advances, the Gross Score is getting smaller: over time, golf scores are getting smaller, meaning I am improving!

    • This effect is clearer than course_rating, as the magnitude of the t value is larger (and greater than 1), and is evident on the time-series graph of the Scoring plot, where Gross Score is simply getting smaller, overall and independent of course, over time (further along the x-axis).
